Last week, BUSINESS WEEK pointed out that the 1964 First Growth Clarets, when they arrive three years hence, will probably command $125-$135 the case! We are inclined to agree with this estimate. If this be so, the rare old great clarets listed below do not simply represent good value—but sensational bargains. The clarets listed below have the advan- tage of ten years of aging —the capacity of being enjoyed today—and the certainty of at least another decade of great life ahead. Most of them can be acquired during this sale, at prices that are below what you will ultimately pay for the ‘just-being-born’ 1964s.

Since here are rarities, no longer commercially available, we can only urge quick acquisition before depletion sets in and be forced to say ‘‘no more left.’’ We might also add that practically all of these prices will be atleast 10% higher starting December Ist.
